            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ari Cohen is a product of San Francisco\u2019s unique cultural fusion, born to a pragmatic Israeli engineer father and a warm, artistic American-Jewish mother from the East Coast. Growing up in the Richmond District, his childhood was a tangle of wires, circuit boards, and the persistent smell of solder. While his father envisioned a prestigious engineering degree, Ari was more interested in the immediate magic of making things work\u2014rewiring stereos, building computers, and bringing discarded electronics back to life.\n\nHe dutifully enrolled in Electrical Engineering at San Francisco State, but the abstract theory felt distant and suffocating. Ari craved tangible results. The turning point came during his third year when, facing a semester of advanced calculus, he dropped out to take a job with a small audio-visual installation company. The decision caused a rift with his father, but for Ari, it was a liberation. He quickly mastered the trade, his partial degree giving him a deep understanding of the principles behind the practice.\n\nWhen the smart home revolution began, Ari was perfectly positioned. He founded \"Seamless Integration,\" his own A/V and smart home company, just as the tech elite began demanding automated lighting, security, and entertainment systems in their Pacific Heights and Noe Valley homes. His reputation for meticulous work and an ability to translate complex tech into simple terms for his wealthy clients allowed his income to soar.\n\nNow 42, Ari lives in a small bungalow in the Outer Sunset. The 9.5-mile commute in his gear-laden van across the city is a daily ritual, a bridge between his tranquil, foggy neighborhood and the high-strung world of his clients. He's amicably divorced, the long hours building his business having taken their toll on his marriage years ago. His social life is a tight circle of old friends and fellow tradespeople.\n\nHis hope isn't for more wealth, but for more time. Ari dreams of training a successor to handle the demanding daily schedule, freeing him to focus on passion projects, like restoring vintage audio equipment, and perhaps finally taking a long trip to visit family in Tel Aviv. He feels a deep, craftsman\u2019s connection to San Francisco\u2014not to the ephemeral apps, but to the physical homes he wires, leaving his invisible, elegant mark on the city's very framework."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being thirteen, hunched over the guts of his mother\u2019s Marantz receiver on the Richmond District garage floor. His father handed him a soldering iron, explaining the schematic\u2019s logic. But when Ari finished and the warm, static-laced sound of a record filled the dusty air, he felt a magic that had nothing to do with diagrams. It was the first time he understood that his joy came not from theory, but from bringing something silent back to life. That feeling, a craftsman's secret pride, became his compass.\n\n2.\nThe conversation with his father about dropping out of SF State wasn't loud. It was worse. It was the heavy silence in their living room, his father\u2019s engineering textbooks visible on the shelf behind him. Ari felt the crushing weight of his father's disappointment, a physical pressure in his chest. But beneath it was a terrifying, exhilarating lightness\u2014the feeling of finally choosing his own path. That moment taught him that the hardest decisions were often the most honest ones, shaping his fierce professional independence.\n\n3.\nIt was a Pacific Heights mansion, and the tech CEO client was famously impatient. Ari ignored the complex schematics. Instead, he simply asked, \u201cWhat do you want the house to *feel* like when you walk in?\u201d The man paused, thrown off. For the next hour, they talked about light, music, and mood. The moment the CEO smiled, finally understanding the system as a feeling, not a function, Ari knew he had found his calling. It wasn't about selling tech; it was about translating it into human comfort.\n\n4.\nShortly after his divorce, he sat alone in his new Outer Sunset bungalow. He had just spent the weekend perfecting his own smart home system\u2014the audio was flawless, the lighting immaculate. Yet, the silence in the house was absolute, a hollow contrast to the technical perfection surrounding him. He realized with a quiet ache that he had built a perfectly connected home but had let his most important human connection fray. It was then that his ambition shifted from wealth to time.\n\n5.\nLast year, inside the wall of a minimalist Noe Valley smart home, Ari paused before sealing the panel. Next to the sterile, blinking server rack, he carefully placed a small, vintage vacuum tube from a 1960s amplifier. It served no function; it was a secret signature, a warm, analog soul hidden within the digital skeleton. It was his private mark on the city\u2019s frame\u2014a testament that behind every seamless system was a craftsman\u2019s imperfect, human touch."
